<DOC><DOCNO> AP900228-0103 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-90 1315EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Britain-War     02-28 0193</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Britain-War,0198</SECOND><HEAD>British Remember 1940 Air Battles</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Commemorations to mark the 50th anniversary of theBattle of Britain in World War II opened on Wednesday with adisplay of paintings, drawings and sculpture at the Royal Air ForceMuseum in Hendon.   Most members of the Guild of Aviation Artists who produced theworks at the north London museum's request were not born when theRAF Hurricanes and Spitfires met the German Luftwaffe over southernEngland in the summer of 1940.   The exhibits depict the aircraft and people of the battle onboth sides and cost from $75 for a pencil drawing of a pilot to$25,000 for a large oil of three Spitfires by Frank Wootton, aleading aviation artist during the war.   The museum is the largest in Europe devoted to aviation.   ``We have planned an extensive program of events for theanniversary year and in April we will open a major exhibition aboutthe battle, with British and German aircraft which took part init,'' said the director, Michael Fopp.   Memorial ceremonies to remember those who fought and died willtake place throughout Britain during the summer.</TEXT></DOC>